08037nam a22010455i 9780812291070DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)952785611  a97808122910707 a10.9783/97808122910702doi  a(DE-B1597)451277  a(OCoLC)904647633  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aF2231.5b.S73 2015eb 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a980223  aLB 526552rvk0(DE-625)rvk/90567:99600aState Theory and Andean Politics :bNew Approaches to the Study of Rule /ced. by David Nugent, Christopher Krupa. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b2 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tChapter 1. Off-Centered States: Rethinking State Theory Through an Andean Lens -- tPart I. Critical Phenomenologies of Rule -- tChapter 2. The Idea of the State in Colombia: An Analysis from the Periphery -- tChapter 3. Respatializing the State from the Margins: Reflections on the Camba Autonomy Movement in Santa Cruz, Bolivia -- tChapter 4. State Formation and Class Politics in Colombia -- tPart II. Off-Centered Morphologies of State -- tChapter 5. Cadastral Politics: Property Wars and State Realism in Highland Ecuador -- tChapter 6. New Arenas of State Action in Highland Ecuador: Public Health and State Formation, c. 1925–1950 -- tChapter 7. The State and Indigenous Women in Ecuador, 1925–1975 -- tPart III. Fear, Fantasy, and Delusion -- tChapter 8. Haunting the Modern Andean State: Colonial Legacies of Race and Civilization -- tChapter 9. Appearances to the Contrary: Fantasy, Fear, and Displacement in Twentieth-Century Peruvian State Formation -- tPart IV. Cross-Border Processes of Statecraft -- tChapter 10. Notes on the Formation of the Andean Colonial State -- tChapter 11. The Aspirational State: State Effects in Putumayo -- tPart V. Theoretical Reflections -- tChapter 12. Off-Centered States: An Appreciation -- tChapter 13. Viewing States from the Global South -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the last few decades, Andean states have seen major restructuring of the organization, leadership, and reach of their governments. With these political tremors come major aftershocks, regarding both definitions and expectations: What is a state? Who or what makes it up, and where does it reside? In what capacity can the state be expected to right wrongs, raise people up, protect them from harm, maintain order, or provide public services? What are its powers and responsibilities?State Theory and Andean Politics attempts to answer these questions and more through an examination of the ongoing process of state creation in Andean nations. Focusing on the everyday, extraofficial, and frequently invisible or partially concealed permutations of rule in the lives of Andean people, the essays explore the material and cultural processes by which states come to appear as real and tangible parts of everyday life. In particular, they focus on the critical role of emotion, imagination, and fantasy in generating belief in the state, among the governed and the governing alike. This approach pushes beyond the limits of the state as conventionally understood to consider how "nonstate" acts of governance intersect with official institutions of government, while never being entirely determined by them or bound to their authorizing agendas. State Theory and Andean Politics asserts that the state is not simply an institutional-bureaucratic apparatus but one of many forces vying for a claim to legitimate political dominion.Featuring an impressive array of Andeanist scholars as well as eminent state theorists Akhil Gupta and Gyanendra Pandey, State Theory and Andean Politics makes a bold and novel claim about the nature of states and state-making that deepens understanding not only of the Andes and the Global South but of the world at large.Contributors: Kim Clark, Nicole Fabricant, Lesley Gill, Akhil Gupta, Christopher Krupa, David Nugent, Gyanendra Pandey, Mercedes Prieto, Maria Clemencia Ramírez, Irene Silverblatt, Karen Spalding, Winifred Tate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aNation-buildingvAndes Region. 0aNation-buildingvPhilosophy. 0aNation-buildingxPhilosophy. 0aNation-buildingzAndes Region. 0aPolitical anthropologyvAndes Region. 0aPolitical anthropologyzAndes Region. 0aPolitical anthropology. 4aFolklore. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aFolklore.  aLinguistics.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.1 aClark, A. Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFabricant, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGill, Lesley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGupta, Akhil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrupa, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrupa, Christopher, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNugent, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNugent, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPandey, Gyanendra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrieto, Mercedes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRamírez, María Clemencia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilverblatt, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpalding, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4http